      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if i'm using a generator, i'm basically just pulling one row at a time through the loop instead of the whole thing. but if my script is still crashing even after i switched to generators, what's usually the culprit? like, if the generator itself isn't the problem, what else could be causing the memory to just vanish or get eaten up like that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If even with generators you're hitting memory issues, the culprit often lies in what you *do* with each row inside the loop. For instance, if you are reading a massive string chunk from the CSV and then performing intensive operations like complex regex matching or loading subsets into large data structures inside the loop, those temporary objects can still consume huge amounts of RAM. It's also worth checking if any Pandas functions you use *after* reading the row are implicitly trying to buffer large amounts of data.",
      "source": "target",
